						<div class="post_wrapper" style="padding-top:0;">
							<div class="post_inner_wrapper">
						    	<div class="post_wrapper_inner">
										<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
								        
										<p>It may be <a href="https://lithub.com/looks-like-the-chicago-sun-times-used-ai-to-write-a-reading-list-and-wound-up-with-slop/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the summer of slop</a>, but that doesn&#8217;t mean there aren&#8217;t some great books out there. Here are the novels coming out this summer that the humans on the Literary Hub staff have read and loved, and would like to recommend to you.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><script id="9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23">(new Image()).src = 'https://capi.connatix.com/tr/si?token=546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff&cid=86b7c382-5e20-4129-84db-dea768f4d688';  cnx.cmd.push(function() {    cnx({      playerId: "546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff"    }).render("9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23");  });</script></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254590" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/farr1/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/farr1.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="farr1" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/farr1-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/farr1.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254590" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/farr1.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/farr1.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/farr1-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/farr1-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/farr1-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/farr1-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Darrow Farr, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593833247" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Bombshell</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Pamela Dorman, May 27</strong></h4>
<p>A May book that made it onto a strict June-August roundup, <em>The Bombshell </em>couldnâ€™t be ignored for what it is: the truest encapsulation of the summer novel. Itâ€™s bold, brash, and deeply absorbing. I read it in two long days spent at the beach, baking in the heat, taking cold dips in the water, returning once again to the world that Darrow Farr has created. The sun, the water, the sand, all felt like extensions of the hot and crackling world evoked in these pages. Set in Corsica in the 90s, a young woman named SÃ©verine, known for her powerful confidence and sexuality, is kidnapped from her politician fatherâ€™s home. The kidnappers are Corsican nationalists who are executing their most dramatic ploy for liberation by keeping SÃ©verine their hostage. But theyâ€™re out of their depths, these three young men, and each one ends up under SÃ©verineâ€™s spell, with both tender, and violent consequences. Glittering and dangerous, much like beauty, much like the promises of youth, the story of SÃ©verine and her captors is one that will get its hooks into you. Drama and destruction, passion and power, all add up to a combustible combination in this tale of conquest, freedom, and sexual awakening.Â â€“<em>Julia Hass, Book Marks Assistant Editor</em></p>
<h4><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254591" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/choi1/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/choi1.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="choi1" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/choi1-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/choi1.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254591" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/choi1.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/choi1.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/choi1-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/choi1-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/choi1-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/choi1-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Susan Choi,Â <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374616373" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Flashlight</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>FSG, June 3</strong></h4>
<p>You might have caught a piece of National Book Award winner Susan Choiâ€™s knotty, haunted new novel when itÂ <a href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/09/07/flashlight" class="external" target="_blank">appeared in theÂ <em>New Yorker</em></a> all the way back in August 2020. Spanning more than seven decades, itâ€™s a bleak, unsentimental character study of three damaged souls trying and failing to claw back to one another. Serk is an ethnic Korean, born in Japan, whose family is ruptured by post-war regime change. Jaded and taciturn, he moves to the US, where he meets Anne, a white midwestern woman whose fling with an older man ends with the birth of a son she is immediately forced to give up. Years later, Serk brings Anne and their ten-year-old daughter Louisa to Japan for his visiting professorship, where a bizarre tragedy fractures the family beyond repair. Not an easy read, but an aching, beautiful, utterly compelling one. <em>â€“Dan Sheehan, Book Marks Editor-in-Chief</em></p>
<h4><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254592" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/conklin1/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/conklin1.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="conklin1" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/conklin1-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/conklin1.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254592" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/conklin1.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/conklin1.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/conklin1-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/conklin1-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/conklin1-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/conklin1-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Lydi Conklin,Â <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781646222513" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Songs of No Provenance</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Catapult, June 3</strong></h4>
<p>I can honestly say I can&#8217;t compareÂ <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781646222513" class="external" target="_blank">Songs of No Provenance</a>,</em>Â Lydi Conklin&#8217;s debut novel, to anything else I&#8217;ve ever read. This book about an indie songwriter with a bad reputation (in the Joan Jett sense) is interested in the corrupting forces of celebrity and shame. Our thrillingly gnarly motor, Joan Vole, is monomaniacal about her work and her water sports. She lives to feel the worship of her dedicated fanbase. But when she takes her onstage antics to a new, disturbing height, reckonings follow and tabs must be paid. In Joan, Conklin&#8217;s drawn a crusty, vexing, and totally singular protagonist. I appreciated that this story begins precisely where many others with the same furniture tend to end. Conklin aims to autopsize the aftermath. What happens on theÂ <em>other</em> side of the apology tour? What really follows when you finally name your kink? <em>â€“Brittany Allen, Staff Writer</em></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<h4><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254593" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/schaefer1/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schaefer1.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="schaefer1" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schaefer1-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schaefer1.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254593" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schaefer1.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schaefer1.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schaefer1-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schaefer1-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schaefer1-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schaefer1-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Lucas Schaefer,Â <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668030707" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Slip</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Simon &amp; Schuster, June 3</strong></h4>
<p><strong>Â </strong>Most authors, let alone most debut authors, wouldnâ€™t attempt a 500-page tragicomic Texan epic that tackles race, class, gender, sexuality, police violence, mental illness, immigration, boxing, and clowning, but Lucas Schaefer is not most authors. His first novel is the story of an endearingly malcontent teenage boyâ€”sixteen-year-old Nathaniel Rothsteinâ€”sent to spend the summer of 1998 with his aunt and uncle in Austin, where a swaggering Haitian ex-boxer takes him under his wing. Just as Nathaniel is coming into his own at the boxing gym, he disappears. With this incident as a fulcrum, Schafer builds us a big, bold, brave, brilliant, beast of a novel. Uproarious and tender, epic in scope and intimate in portraiture, crammed with so many outlandish incidents and exquisitely rendered characters youâ€™ll wonder how one novel can possibly contain them all, but Schaefer pulls it off with aplomb. As fearless and enjoyable a debut as youâ€™re likely to read this year. <em>â€“DS</em></p>
<h4><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254594" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/schwab1/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schwab1.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="schwab1" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schwab1-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schwab1.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254594" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schwab1.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schwab1.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schwab1-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schwab1-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schwab1-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/schwab1-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>V.E. Schwab, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250320520" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Bury Our Bones in the Midnight Soil</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Tor Books, June 10</strong></h4>
<p><em>The Invisible Life of Addie LaRue</em> made V.E. Schwab an international superstar but I tell you what: this book is even better. I&#8217;ve always loved the messy sexiness of Anne Rice&#8217;s Vampire Chronicles books and the idea of Schwab doing messy sexy vampires is a dream come trueâ€”Sabine, Charlotte, and Alice are as etched in my mind as Louis, Lestat, and Armand. But it&#8217;s more than just a pastiche: Schwab brings her deep well of empathy to bear on questions of immortality, love, rage, and what a person owes to a society that doesn&#8217;t care for them. It&#8217;s a novel bigger on the inside, a quality that&#8217;s another of Schwab&#8217;s many seemingly magical talents. It might be my favorite book of the year so far. <em>â€“Drew Broussard, Podcasts Editor</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254595" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/walter-3/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/walter.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="walter" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/walter-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/walter.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254595" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/walter.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/walter.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/walter-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/walter-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/walter-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/walter-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Jess Walter,Â <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780062868145" class="external" target="_blank">So Far Gone</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Harper, June 10</strong></h4>
<p>This is a snack of a novel. Specifically? That snack is jerky. Walter, whose polyphonic sensibility first charmed me inÂ <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780061928178" class="external" target="_blank">Beautiful Ruins</a>,</em>Â has here made something salty, sinewy, and satisfying from fairly tough material.Â <em>So Far Gone</em> follows Rhys, a retired newspaperman turned off-the-grid Thoreau acolyte, as he falls into a madcap quest to save his estranged daughter and grandchildren from the clutches of an evangelical militia/cult. In lesser hands, the family&#8217;s unfortunately topical adversaries could be but straw bogeymen or non pareil Darth Vaders. But Walter&#8217;s interested in the fear that draws people toward cruel and senseless ideologies. Full of insightful arias, shimmeringly weird little details, and a characteristic hometown love for the Pacific Northwest, this book reminded me of Cassavetes&#8217; hard-boiled anti-heroes, and the best kinds of caper flicks. <em>â€“BA</em></p>
