<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Karim Dimechkie,Â <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780316581189" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Uproar</em></a><br />
Little, Brown and Company, June 17</strong><strong>Â </strong></h4>
<p>Karim Dimechkieâ€™s unbearably tense (yet frequently very funny) second novel is the story of a white Brooklyn social workerâ€”a good man, deeply invested in the idea of his own goodnessâ€”and the incident that blows his life apart. Sharif badly needs a raise. His wife Adjoua, a progressive Black novelist with overbearing parents, is pregnant with their immunocompromised child. His 150-pound Pitbull mastiff needs to be housed somewhere. When one of his former clients, an undocumented Haitian immigrant named Emmanuel, agrees to care for the dog while Adjoua is in labor, Sharif thinks heâ€™s caught a break, until an ugly confrontation with Emmanuelâ€™s teenage son creates a maelstrom that threatens to destroy everything. A brilliant, shapeshifting, deeply insightful examination of race and class, marriage and modern masculinity, this one will stay with me for a long time. <em>â€“DS</em></p>
<h4><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254599" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/mendelsund/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/mendelsund.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="mendelsund" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/mendelsund-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/mendelsund.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254599" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/mendelsund.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/mendelsund.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/mendelsund-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/mendelsund-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/mendelsund-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/mendelsund-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Peter Mendelsund, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374619077" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Weepers</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>FSG, June 17</strong></h4>
<p>An extraordinarily unique and surreal cowboy novel, <em>Weepers</em> is a story unlike any other. The novel is set in a world where emotion has been seeped out of humanity: thereâ€™s too much to feel, too much to grieve, so the citizens of this universe have been nullified, neutralized, â€œhealedâ€, is one word for it. In a world that has been desiccated of its resources, and of its ability to care about each other, the people in this novel donâ€™t cry anymore. They donâ€™t experience devastation. They go about their days, they take the many heartbreaks of life in stride.</p>
<p>Which is where the â€œweepersâ€ come in: a hired group whose job is to feel. They attend funerals and memorials, and take on the weight of the sadness for the people who have learned to be numb. But even the weepers are growing tired of carrying this weight. Then â€œthe Kidâ€ shows up and joins their forces, a messianic and silent character who provokes depth wherever he goes. The weepers, as well as anyone who comes into contact with the Kid, are given a new understanding of the true sorrows and emotions that a heart can hold. Mystical and mysterious, <em>Weepers </em>offers its readers an entrancing story of dystopia and death, a novel just as magnetic as the Kid himself.Â â€“Â­<em>JH</em></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
