<h4><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254602" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/stevens/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/stevens.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="stevens" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/stevens-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/stevens.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254602" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/stevens.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/stevens.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/stevens-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/stevens-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/stevens-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/stevens-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Nell Stevens, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781324110699" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Original</a><br />
</em>W.W. Norton, July 1</strong></h4>
<p>Iâ€™ve been proselytizing Nell Stevensâ€™ first book, <em>Briefly, A Delicious Life</em> since it came out a few years ago. Itâ€™s one of my all-time favorites, the kind of book thatâ€™s always in the back of my mind, that I come back to all the time. So I was beyond excited to find out thereâ€™s a new Nell Stevens book coming out this summer! And itâ€™s a total banger! I literally couldnâ€™t put this book down. I thought about it constantly while I was reading it. If thatâ€™s not a recommendation, I donâ€™t know what is.</p>
<p>The novel follows a young woman, Grace, who secretly becomes an incredible art forger. Just as she begins to use her talent professionally, a man shows up claiming to be her long-lost cousinâ€”but Graceâ€™s face-blindness makes it impossible for her to know whether heâ€™s really her cousin or not. Itâ€™s a novel about fakes and copies and originality and the meaning of art and it has so many delicious layers to unwrap. Itâ€™s like <em>F for Fake</em> (1973) by way of <em>Jane Eyre</em>&gt; or <em>O Caledonia</em>. Itâ€™s thoughtful and haunting and beautifully written. A perfect gothic novel to add to your summer reading list! <em>â€“MC</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254604" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/runcie/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/runcie.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="runcie" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/runcie-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/runcie.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254604" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/runcie.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/runcie.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/runcie-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/runcie-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/runcie-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/runcie-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Charlotte Runcie, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9780385551076" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Bring the House Down</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Doubleday, July 8</strong></h4>
<p>I&#8217;m still a theater kid at heart (no matter how much time continues to pass without auditioning) and there&#8217;s nothing like a summer festivalâ€”and of all the summer festivals, the Edinburgh Fringe is probably the wildest and most magical. Runcie (a journalist who covered the Fringe for years) gets theater right in this excellent debut novel. It follows a female critic who watches her male colleague suddenly become the focus of an excoriating one-woman-show after he gave it a bad review. It&#8217;s a brilliant look at the utter madness that is the Fringe, a deep consideration of criticism and art (and parenthood as a professional), and a fiery reminder that we still have so far to go when it comes to men behaving poorly and getting away with it. Like the title says, it&#8217;s time to bring the house down. <em>â€“DB</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254605" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/carrington-3/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/carrington.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="carrington" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/carrington-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/carrington.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254605" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/carrington.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/carrington.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/carrington-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/carrington-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/carrington-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/carrington-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Leonora Carrington,Â <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781681378947" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The Stone Door</em></a><br />
NYRB, July 15</strong></h4>
<p><em>The Stone Door</em>Â opens in a forest, on a house composed of competing styles, â€œas if the architect had wrought a terrible revenge on his school days.â€ Itâ€™s a fitting opening image for a book that is also a pastiche of styles, strange and tough to characterize with the epic sweep of myth, the significance of parable, and the magical logic of a fairy tale. As a child, Carrington was raised on fairy tales in an English manor house and as an adult was caught, tragically at times, in the upheaval of WWII Europe and in the constant company of Surrealists. All of these influences swirl in the book, and for such a short novel,Â <em>The Stone Door</em>Â morphs a lot. It&#8217;s impossible to anticipate where Carrington will go: the adventure can be grounded, as in the smaller, domestic scenes, or more grand, like when the main character must negotiate with a giant who wants to skin him.Â <em>The Stone Door</em> is a fascinating and unsettled book, that always seems to be teetering on the edge of something dark, something mad: â€œHardly daring to touch what I want to say, yet knowing that if I had enough space around me it would be a piercing shriek.â€ â€“<em>JF</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254606" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/clune/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/clune.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="clune" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/clune-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/clune.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254606" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/clune.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/clune.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/clune-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/clune-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/clune-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/clune-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Michael Clune, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593834428" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Pan</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Penguin Press, July 22</strong></h4>
<p>Though he works in many modes, Clune is best known for his 2013 cult memoir about heroin addiction, White Out, which was recently reissued by McNally Editions. In his first novel, he investigates panic, which when it manifests in the life of a teenage boy, takes on psychedelic, and then cosmic, and then, perhaps, divine proportions. The book explodes the central dilemma of the panic attackâ€”what is real? and then, whether real or illusory, on what plane can I approach?â€”and wraps it all up in a moving coming-of-age story. <em>â€“Emily Temple, Managing Editor</em></p>
<h4><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254614" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/hakmi2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/hakmi2.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="hakmi2" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/hakmi2-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/hakmi2.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254614" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/hakmi2.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/hakmi2.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/hakmi2-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/hakmi2-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/hakmi2-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/hakmi2-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Tehila Hakimi, tr. Joanna Chen, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780143138662" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Hunting in America</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Viking, July 22</strong></h4>
<p>Tehila Hakimiâ€™s award-winning <em>Hunting in America</em> is available in English for the first time: an enigmatic puzzle of a novel with a wry, mesmerizing voice, it goes down easy in a one-sitting read. Not to say that itâ€™s gentle, or comfortable. Itâ€™s sly, and eerie, and keeps you guessing, and on edge, but in a way where you canâ€™t stop turning the pages. It centers around a woman who relocates from Israel to America for her corporate job, and while reckoning with her new country, her new office, her new mundanities, develops a fixation on hunting. Stalking prey, feeling stalked herself, feeling the weight of a country and its expectations, it evokes Samantha Schweblin and Han Kang in its surreality and daring specificity. Pervasively unsettling, both too alien and too familiar, <em>Hunting in America</em> coolly illustrates the complicity that both Israeli and Americans have in a gun-touting culture, and the insidious ways that violence can seep into our consciousness. â€“<em>JH<br />
</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254608" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/yee/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/yee.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="yee" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/yee-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/yee.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254608" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/yee.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/yee.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/yee-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/yee-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/yee-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/yee-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Katie Yee, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668084212" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Maggie; or, A Man and a Woman Walk Into a Bar</em></a><br />
Summit Books, July 22</strong></h4>
<p>I can&#8217;t say I went into Katie Yee&#8217;s debut novel as an unbiased reader. I had the pleasure of reading Katie&#8217;s work for years when she was an editor at this very website. Still, personal relationships aside, I feel confident in recommending Maggie; Or, A Man and a Woman Walk Into a Bar to anyone who craves the embrace of a novel that perfectly weaves grief with warmth and wit. We follow the novel&#8217;s narrator as she absorbs the one-two punch of her husband&#8217;s affair (for which he apologizes, but does not ask for forgivenessâ€”so, divorce) and a breast cancer diagnosis, while she meditates on the quotidian joys and betrayals of relationships, the strangeness of parenthood, the loss of health and of identity, how to nail storytime, and what a joke even is. Funny, sad, kind, and deeply tender, this is a book that goes down like a treat, and stays with you the way only the wisest novels can.Â  <em>â€“JG</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254609" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/gross/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/gross.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="gross" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/gross-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/gross.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254609" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/gross.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/gross.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/gross-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/gross-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/gross-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/gross-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Jessica Gross, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781419778988" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Open Wide</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Abrams, August 5</strong></h4>
<p>For a while, I thought that the promised derangement in Open Wide was going to be the regular kind: a woman who becomes much too obsessed with the man she&#8217;s dating, to the point where she ruins everything. (Is that what happens? It&#8217;s debatable.) But without giving anything away, because I am glad that I was not prepared for what actually happens: the promised derangement is much more deranged than that. It&#8217;s funny and demented and a little stupid, which I mean as a compliment, and when it starts, it doesn&#8217;t stop. Gross is excellent at pushing things to their logical conclusion, and then pushing them a little further than that, which is honestly all I want in my literature. <em>â€“ET</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254611" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/adrian/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/adrian.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="adrian" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/adrian-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/adrian.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254611" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/adrian.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/adrian.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/adrian-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/adrian-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/adrian-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/adrian-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Emily Adrian, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780316584517" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Seduction Theory</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Little, Brown, August 12</strong></h4>
<p>At last, a book that is actually just as fun as it sounds. This a novel in the form of an MFA thesis, written to expose a revolving door of love affairs of the professors who are reading it, not to mention the graduate student who wrote it. I know. I know! A little bit postmodern, a little bit sexy, and quite funny indeed, you will feel both smarter and more indulgent than usual while youâ€™re reading it (especially if you&#8217;ve ever been in any kind of writing program, or had any kind of insane crush), and really, isnâ€™t that the best way to feel, in the summer or otherwise? <em>â€“ET</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="254613" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/citchens/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/citchens.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="citchens" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/citchens-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/citchens.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-254613" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/citchens.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/citchens.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/citchens-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/citchens-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/citchens-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/citchens-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Addie Citchens, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374609337" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Dominion</em></a><br />
</strong><strong>FSG, August 19Â </strong></h4>
<p>I&#8217;ve been waiting for this novel ever since stumbling uponÂ <a href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2024/02/12/that-girl-fiction-addie-citchens" class="external" target="_blank">this perfectÂ <em>New Yorker</em>Â story</a>Â last winter. And<em>Â DominionÂ </em>did not disappoint. This stellar, utterly assured debut about the larger-than-life father and son about whom all congregants of the Seven Seals M.B. Church orbit simply crackles on the sentence level. We&#8217;re held in the minds of Priscilla, &#8220;First Lady&#8221; to the Reverend Sabre Winfrey, and Diamond Bailey, adoring girlfriend of the preacher&#8217;s golden son. These left of center women are charming, witty, sometimes heartbreaking chroniclers of the men who govern their lives. But the novel is as much a drama as it is a character study. Citchens is interested in the cult of patriarchy, and the many sins thoughtless worship enables.</p>
<p>Kiese Laymon has praised Citchens for capturing a &#8220;breathing&#8221; Mississippi with gumption. I&#8217;m another happy convert on the strength of this bright new voice. <em>â€“BA</em></p>
										
																				
																		
